         <h1>Tadeus Reichstein, 99, Dies; Won Nobel for Cortisone Work </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Dr. Tadeus Reichstein , a Swiss chemist who shared the Nobel Prize in medicine with two Americans for their work with cortisone , died Thursday at his home in Basel , Switzerland . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 99 . <br><blue>3</blue>In the 1930 's and 1940 's , Dr. Reichstein isolated several biologically active substances including corticosterone , the anti-inflammatory agent now known as cortisone , from hormones produced in the adrenal glands , which are located above the kidneys . <br><blue>4</blue>Dr. Reichstein studied organic chemistry at the Zurich Eidgenossische Technische Hochschule , where he earned his Ph.D. in 1922 . <br><blue>5</blue>After a brief time in industry , he returned to the technical institute as a lecturer . <br><blue>6</blue>In 1933 , he had his first great success when he developed a process for synthesizing Vitamin C that helped lead to its mass production . <br><blue>7</blue>In the mid-1930 's he began his pioneering work on the hormones produced in the adrenal glands . <br><blue>8</blue>By 1937 Dr. Reichstein had isolated corticosterone . <br><blue>9</blue>At the same time , similar independent research on cortisone was being done in America by Prof. Edward C. Kendall at the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota . <br><blue>10</blue>In the 1940 's , he and Dr. Philip S. Hench , his colleague at the clinic , began testing cortisone , which Dr. Kendall had named Compound E , as a treatment for arthritis . <br><blue>11</blue>One of Dr. Reichstein 's assistants , Dr. Marguerite Steiger , subsequently synthesized a form of cortisone that was named deoxy-corticosterone . <br><blue>12</blue>At the time it proved useful in the treatment of Addison 's disease , a condition in which the adrenal glands do not produce enough hormones . <br><blue>13</blue>In 1938 , Dr. Reichstein joined the faculty of the University of Basel , where he continued his research . <br><blue>14</blue>By 1946 , he and his assistants had isolated 29 different steroids produced by the adrenal glands . <br><blue>15</blue>In 1950 , Doctors Reichstein , Kendall and Hench were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in medicine for '' their discoveries concerning the suprarenal cortex hormones , their structure and biological effects . '' <br><blue>16</blue>Dr. Reichstein retired from the University of Basel in 1967 , but remained active in research until recently . <br><blue>17</blue>In 1992 , he was among 63 Nobel laureates to sign an appeal to the world 's governments to use their influence to end fighting in Bosnia and Herzegovina . <br><blue>18</blue>Tadeus Reichstein was born July 20 , 1897 , in Wloclawek , Poland . <br><blue>19</blue>His family lived in Kiev , Ukraine , and Berlin before settling in Zurich in 1905 . <br><blue>20</blue>They became Swiss citizens in 1914 . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>1940 's</m_str> (3_6) 	<m_str>1940 's</m_str> (10_3) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>His family</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>They</m_str> (20_1) 	<br><blue>3(3)</blue>: <m_str>their</m_str> (15_20) 	<m_str>Reichstein , Kendall and Hench</m_str> (15_5) 	<m_str>their</m_str> (15_28) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>Dr. Reichstein 's assistants</m_str> (11_3) 	<m_str>his assistants</m_str> (14_6) 	<br><blue>5(25)</blue>: <m_str>His</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>Dr. Reichstein</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>Dr. Reichstein</m_str> (8_3) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_14) 	<m_str>Dr. Reichstein</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_16) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (5_8) 	<m_str>Dr. Reichstein</m_str> (13_4) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (17_4) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_4) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_27) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (6_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_16) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (13_18) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_11) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_4) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_6) 	<m_str>Tadeus Reichstein</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_13) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_5) 	<m_str>Dr. Reichstein</m_str> (3_9) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_7) 	<m_str>Dr. Reichstein 's</m_str> (11_3) 	